I need to find the probability of at least one match when rolling an n-sided die n times, where a match occurs if side i appears on trial i.

This is a classic matching problem (also known as the derangement problem or problème des rencontres).

The probability of at least one match is given by:
$$P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - P(\text{no matches})$$

The probability of no matches (a derangement) is:
$$P(\text{no matches}) = \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{(-1)^k}{k!}$$

This can be written as:
$$P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{(-1)^k}{k!}$$

As n → ∞, we recognize that:
$$\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^k}{k!} = e^{-1}$$

Therefore:
$$\lim_{n \to \infty} P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - e^{-1} = 1 - \frac{1}{e}$$

Calculating the numerical value:
$$1 - \frac{1}{e} = 1 - \frac{1}{2.71828...} = 1 - 0.36788... = 0.63212...$$

Rounding to a reasonable number of significant figures:

