I need to find $D_e$ (the dissociation energy at the minimum of the potential energy curve) from $D_0$ (the dissociation energy from the ground vibrational state).

The relationship between $D_e$ and $D_0$ is:

$$D_e = D_0 + E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)$$

where $E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)$ is the zero-point vibrational energy.

The zero-point vibrational energy is given by:

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega_e\left(1 - 2x_e\right)$$

Or more commonly expressed in wavenumber units:

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}\frac{\nu_e}{c}\left(1 - 2\nu_e x_e/\nu_e\right) \times hc$$

Simplifying, the zero-point energy in cm⁻¹ units is:

$$\tilde{E}_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}\nu_e/c - \nu_e x_e/c$$

Given:
- $\nu_e/c = 1405.65$ cm⁻¹
- $\nu_e x_e/c = 23.20$ cm⁻¹

Calculate the zero-point energy in cm⁻¹:

$$\tilde{E}_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}(1405.65) - 23.20 = 702.825 - 23.20 = 679.625 \text{ cm}^{-1}$$

Convert cm⁻¹ to eV using the conversion factor: 1 eV = 8065.54 cm⁻¹

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{679.625}{8065.54} = 0.08428 \text{ eV}$$

Now calculate $D_e$:

$$D_e = D_0 + E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = 2.4287 + 0.08428 = 2.5130 \text{ eV}$$

