Solution: I need to find P(Y₇ < 27.3), where Y₇ is the 7th order statistic out of 8 observations, and 27.3 is the 70th percentile of the distribution.

**Key Information:**
- We have 8 observations: Y₁ < Y₂ < ... < Y₈
- π₀.₇ = 27.3 (the 70th percentile)
- This means P(X < 27.3) = 0.7 for a single observation

**Finding P(Y₇ < 27.3):**

Y₇ < 27.3 means that at least 7 of the 8 observations are less than 27.3.

The number of observations less than 27.3 follows a binomial distribution with n = 8 and p = 0.7 (the probability that a single observation is less than 27.3).

P(Y₇ < 27.3) = P(at least 7 observations < 27.3)
                = P(exactly 7 < 27.3) + P(exactly 8 < 27.3)

Using the binomial distribution:
- P(exactly 7 < 27.3) = C(8,7) × (0.7)⁷ × (0.3)¹
- P(exactly 8 < 27.3) = C(8,8) × (0.7)⁸ × (0.3)⁰

**Calculating:**

P(exactly 7) = 8 × (0.7)⁷ × 0.3
- (0.7)⁷ = 0.0823543
- 8 × 0.0823543 × 0.3 = 0.1976503

P(exactly 8) = 1 × (0.7)⁸ × 1
- (0.7)⁸ = 0.0576480
- 1 × 0.0576480 = 0.0576480

P(Y₇ < 27.3) = 0.1976503 + 0.0576480 = 0.2552983

Rounding to 3 significant figures: **0.255**

